Project: {project_name} Client: {client_name} Methodology: {methodology} Service Lines: {service_lines}
Project Type Guidance: {project_type_guidance}
SOW Summary: {sow_summary}
Service Line Design Standards: {standards_context}
Platform Combination Patterns (proven integration patterns for this service line mix): {combinations_context}
Generated Requirements Context (if available): {requirements_context}
FORMAT GUIDE ONLY — READ CAREFULLY BEFORE GENERATING: The example below is for a COMPLETELY DIFFERENT fictional project (Meridian Insurance). DO NOT copy any of the following from the example into your output: - Component names (ClaimsIntakeService, PolicySyncAdapter, MeridianApiGateway) - Technology names unless they also appear in THIS project's service lines above - Any SOW requirements or business logic that don't come from THIS project's context The example shows ONLY the structure and depth of each component entry. All content must come from the actual project context above.
FORMAT EXAMPLE (fictional project — structure only):
### Component: [Name — derived from THIS project's actual service lines and SOW] - **Responsibility**: [What this component does — tied to a specific feature or module from the requirements context above] - **Key modules**: [List class/file names using naming conventions of the actual technology — e.g. Apex classes for Salesforce, Script Includes for ServiceNow] - **Communicates with**: [Name other components in THIS design — not vague "integration layer"] - **Technology**: [Actual framework from this project's stack] - **Why it exists**: [Quote an actual FR/NFR ID or SOW constraint from the context above]
END OF FORMAT EXAMPLE.
Now generate the component structure for {project_name} — client {client_name}, service lines: {service_lines}. Every component must be named and justified using the actual project context above. Do not copy names or details from the format example. Output ONLY markdown.
